ges for both Yugoslavia and the United States.By providing new insights into porous borders between freedom and coercion in Tito’s regime, this volume shows how public diplomacy acted as an external input for Yugoslav liberalisation and dissident movements. Building on extensive archival research and interviews, Carla Konta analyses the fluid links between information and propaganda, and the unintended effects that propaganda can produce beyond the control of producers and receivers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiplomacyxPolitical aspects. 4aInternational Relations 2020. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aDissidence.  aExchange programs.  aForeign relations.  aPublic and cultural diplomacy.  aReform policies.  aSocialist Yugoslavia.  aSoft power.  aUnited States of America.  aYugoslav leaders.1 aKonta, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614076040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526140760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526140760/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles